Mangrove forests play host to many different organisms. Some, such as coral, clams, and barnacles cling onto the roots, while fish and other marine life use the intricate roots as protection. Terrestrial life and nesting birds also make use of these habitats above the water, however, mangrove forests provide more than just shelter for wildlife. The roots from mangroves create an important natural barrier that protects shorelines and communities from storms and erosion, and they help to maintain water quality by removing unwanted nutrients and pollutants from the water.

Unfortunately mangrove forests are one of the most threatened tropical ecosystems. With their populations in a huge decline over the past few decades, forest clearing and pollution stemming primarily from aquaculture and agriculture is the main culprit. With climate change (rising sea levels and coastal acidity) and urbanization/coastal development as the second and third biggest factors.

White-faced capuchin monkeys give birth to just one baby at a time, and the mother will care for this baby, carrying it on her back for around the first 6 weeks of it's life. After a few months the infant will start to find insects, fruit, and other food in it's own, while learning from it's mother and other monkeys in the troop, but it will not become fully independent until it is at least 4 years old.

Smoky skies here in Southern Ontario. Canada is facing it's worst start to a wildfire season to date. Nova Scotia alone has already seen over 200 wildfires this year, after low snowfall this winter and extremely dry spring conditions followed by a recent heatwave made the province especially vulnerable to forest fires. Across the country wildfires are on the rise, as similar conditions are putting our provinces and territories at increased risk of new fires starting and existing fires spreading. Be safe & if you're going camping or using the outdoors follow local fire restrictions.

Quite possibly the most beautiful bird I've ever seen. Heading into the cloud forest of Panama I was hoping I would get a chance to see one of these stunning resplendent quetzals, so I prepared by listening to what their calls sound like ahead of time to better my odds.  In the last section of my second hike of the day I heard a familiar sound, a male resplendent quetzal calling for a mate somewhere behind me. I retraced my steps a bit, started looking through the trees, and eventually spotted this beautiful bird perched just above eye level, not far from me.

Swipe right to see it's magnificent tail feathers

I was surprised (and excited) to see one of my favourite animals from back home when I looked out on the trees at @tranquilobay in Panama 🦝 even more interesting is the Jagua fruit they're snacking on here. This fruit is edible, but it has been used by Indigenous groups in South America for another more unique property. When the  juice from the Jagua fruit is extracted and applied to the skin, within a few hours it will stain the skin and develop a dark black/blue colour, creating a temporary tattoo that will fade after a week or two and closely resembles real tattoos when applied properly.
.

Young fawns have spots on their back and sides until they're around 3-4 months old. These spots help break up their visual pattern, as predators don't see colours the way we do. During the day a fawn's parents will leave it alone in fields and on forest floors to avoid attracting predators to the fawn's location, in hopes that it will be able to camouflage itself and go unnoticed.

I've visited this lighthouse many times in the past few years, through rain, shine, sunrise, and sunset, I've captured it in a variety of scenes. Last week I visited it on a rainy evening and found that one light was left on inside, and with a long exposure, that light was just enough to leak through the building and spread to the other windows. It might be my favorite image of this place so far, as it gives it a cool eerie and cinematic feel that suits this location well. 

Which is your favorite? 💡🏠

Plans change, opportunities arise, and you just have to go with the flow. Near the end of the summer I decided I was going to move back out to the west coast before winter & call Squamish home again. I bought a trailer, found a place to rent, got a ski pass for the winter & was ready to move in October. But out of the blue I got a message from a good friend of mine with a new opportunity that I couldn't pass up on. In 11 days I'm going to be moving to Japan until the spring & I can't wait to see what the next 6 months have in store! 

Side note: this means calendars will be shipping earlier than usual, so get your orders in this week! I'll be putting in my final print run at the end of the week. Thanks to everyone who's put an order in already! 😊
